Solution 

1. connect to EC2 instance via AWS Console go to the path 

cd ~/.ssh/ 
ls
you can find authorized_key
if not create it 

ubuntu@ip-172-31-10-194:~$ cd ~/.ssh/
ubuntu@ip-172-31-10-194:~/.ssh$ ls
authorized_keys
ubuntu@ip-172-31-10-194:~/.ssh$ cd a
-bash: cd: a: No such file or directory
ubuntu@ip-172-31-10-194:~/.ssh$ cat authorized_keys 
ssh-rsa  aws_login

In this case I have the file -> what it means is I have private key not the public key that is reason I am getting permission denied

Now generate the public key from CMD 

C:\Users\PC>ssh-keygen -y -f C:\Users\PC\Downloads\aws_login.pem
ssh-rsa 

chmod 700 ~/.ssh
chmod 600 ~/.ssh/authorized_keys


Paste that key in EC2 authorized_key file don't delete the existing one paste it in new line

now try ssh connection 

C:\Users\PC>ssh -i C:\Users\PC\Downloads\aws_login.pem ubuntu@44.201.47.58
